comment_text_display:
Your review is a problem for me, and I'm not trying to be abrasive. I don't think you have long-term experience or have actually tested TVs long-term.

1) OLED is crap. It burns in. If you watch YouTube or sports, or news.... horrid. Will never buy an OLED ever again. They are fine if you only watch non static content. Otherwise, get used to unacceptable artifacts like rectangles and TV logos burned in forever.
2) Having dozens of QLEDs, you don't get their value. They last. They are bright. I can watch them in my pool, in the sun. They can take abuse. Had mine get wet, look like horrid like mountains on the screen, then just fix themselves. Did I mention I could watch in the Texas sun?

I don't have an opinion on mini led, but I am skeptical. I suspect it's cheaper because it doesn't last like QLEDs.

I'll respect the reviews when you show me reviews of TVs you actually use for more than 4 years. You seem to compare specs, not your actual experience.
comment_text_original:

2) Having dozens of QLEDs, you don't get their value. They last. They are bright. I can watch them in my pool, in the sun. They can take abuse. Had mine get wet, look like horrid like mountains on the screen, then just fix themselves. Did I mention I could watch in the Texas sun?

I don't have an opinion on mini led, but I am skeptical. I suspect it's cheaper because it doesn't last like QLEDs.

I'll respect the reviews when you show me reviews of TVs you actually use for more than 4 years. You seem to compare specs, not your actual experience.

comment_text_display:
@@345power no one knows how much a tv could last. After working in electronics store, I realized 2 things:
-There is no brand that we can confidently claim it is long lasting
-All top brands, in the past 5 years, have dropped the quality, especially in the low budget area.

We get daily, different TVs that we send to the service for repairs, some benefiting from the extended warranty, some still covered by the warranty from manufacturer.

My dad had an LG TV from 2015 till 2018, The panel got degraded pretty fast, probably because he used to leave the TV ON 24/7 on Vivid. Now he has a Samsung UHD TV since 2018, it still works, even if the software got a little sluggish, with slightly degraded panel, usually it is easy to spot some black spots while watching football or the background is a lighter color.

In my room I got an LG UHD TV that I use mainly for some casual gaming and for some movies. I got it in 2022, it still works like it should. I also have a 32" Samsung TV (bought in 2016) that I use mostly as a secondary monitor for PC, and from time to time for watching some football, while I am at PC. I only had it once in the service for a motherboard replacement (in 2017). Now the panel is degraded with intense bleeding on the left side of the screen, and software basically unusable, as it became too slow to even use the smart hub. At least the colors are still ok after a little tweaking.

My brother got a Hisense TV (58A7H) in his living room, he bought it in 2022 and it still works as it should. And he also uses a 32" LG HD TV as a secondary monitor for his PC. I bought that TV for him in 2018, it still works as it should, without feeling sluggish, with no perceptible panel degradation.

At the end of the day, all I can say, get whatever you like, and if you can go to a store to test them, it would be even better.

comment_text_display: Wow, I'm SO glad I came across your channel with this review! I'm an older(ish) gal in my 60s who is still rockin' my 18-yo 40" Sony, but I've had my eye on this new Samsung since I would like something a bit bigger with modern inputs for my Roku and a new soundbar. I love to research stuff, but the way everyone nitpicks EVERY little thing started making me second-guess myself until I saw your review. This is all I needed, just to know that I can stream my TV (in my case, YouTube TV) with decent upscaling, in a bright room without distracting reflections. That's it. That's all I need, and I really appreciate that you kept it simple without complicating it more than people need. If I hadn't seen your review, I'd probably still be shopping for a TV until I'm 70😅

comment_text_display: What was your unpleasant experience exactly?:)
comment_text_original: What was your unpleasant experience exactly?:)

comment_text_display: @@dulifuli00I have had my G2 for 2 1/2 years(Feb 2023) and have 2200 hours on it and discovered early summer that I have got dead pixels on the left side of the screen going all the way down from top to bottom. I’m not impressed given how few hours are on the panel. I’d expect it after 5-7 years of use and much higher hour count. I have a Samsung QN90B that I purchased two months earlier than the G2 and it’s still going strong. Thankfully I have the extended warranty from the store so I’ll get the new tv installed and mounted then make a claim, hopefully the store will just give me a new tv and I can sell it or if they just replace the panel I’ll move the tv to my bedroom where it will see next to no use, maybe 20-30 minutes a day.  It was my first OLED and was previously the best tv I had owned but I’ve lost confidence in OLED now so I don’t think I’ll buy another one and might as well take the advantage and go up in size from 77” to 85” which is the maximum possible size my wall will allow.

comment_text_display:
The edge-lit claim for the Q8F was an honest mistake on my part. According to Samsung's and BestBuy's websites, the 55” models and larger are 120Hz and not 60Hz as I mentioned in the video.

I conduct extensive research before producing my long-form videos, and sometimes the information I find is not always accurate. And when this happens, I will correct that info in the description section.

As far as AI is concerned, I use it as a base platform for most of my videos. The AI program I use cannot accurately produce all the technical information I need for my videos, so I usually have to edit most of the AI script to make it my own. Furthermore, I often write my entire script and then place it into the AI program. I also have to choose and upload most of the images I use in my videos.

To sum things up, I put a lot of work into my videos.
